This paper deals with the application of machine learning models to electronic health records, which is a common topic in the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the importance of model uncertainty in medical decision-making, which is relevant to the subfield of computational ethics (cs.CE). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of Bayesian models, which is a common topic in the subfield of cryptography and security (cs.CR). Finally, the paper discusses the potential clinical impact of understanding model uncertainty, which is relevant to the subfield of human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
